@John ezra
Excellent!

And a 'poke' in Scots dialect is used for any sort of  small bag - a poke of sweets, a poke of chips (fries). Also in the expression, to "buy a pig in a poke".

@Phoebe
I thought of uniforms first, too.
Dad's routine of shining his brass insignia was part of daily life when we were small.  The scent of Brasso can take me back there in a twinkling.  (His birthday was December 15th, so of course I thought of him...on what would have been his 113th!)

@Matt

I felt an anti-vibe the entire time. In the end I quite liked the grid, even though I had to look up several things to get some crosses as footholds.

My wife on the other hand solved this quite smoothly.

@Matt
So far, you are the only one claiming this puzzle wasn't Friday strength.  I suspected there might be more comments like yours, for I only needed five 'easy mode' clues (29a, 52a, 54a, 47a and 39a).  It wasn't as brutal as some Friday puzzles.

We do agree it was charming.  I hope to see more puzzles from Mr. Spooner.

